# ─── apps/a2a-agent/.env.example ─────────────────────────────────────
# Copy to `.env` and replace placeholders. The dev workflow normally
# populates these via `scripts/fresh-start.sh` (which runs deploy-local.sh
# and propagates contract addresses); this file documents the shape.

# ─── Networking ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PORT=3100
RPC_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8545
CHAIN_ID=31337
A2A_HOST_BASE=agent.localhost

# ─── Session secret (local-aes ikm) ───────────────────────────────────
# 32 bytes (64 hex chars), 0x-prefixed accepted. Used by the local-aes
# KMS provider as HKDF input keying material.
#
# Sprint 1 W2.2 S1.3 — this env var is CONDITIONAL on the KMS backend:
#   - A2A_KMS_BACKEND=local-aes  → REQUIRED (≥32 bytes hex)
#   - A2A_KMS_BACKEND=aws-kms    + NODE_ENV=production → MUST NOT be set
#       (config.ts refuses to start to avoid carrying an unused master
#        secret in production env; KMS handles data-key generation)
#   - A2A_KMS_BACKEND=aws-kms    + non-prod → tolerated but ignored;
#                                              config.ts logs a warning.
# Dev / fresh-start sets it because the default backend is local-aes.
A2A_SESSION_SECRET=0xbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbb

# ─── KMS-class key-custody backend (KMS migration K0+K1+K2) ──────────
# 'local-aes' → per-row HKDF over A2A_SESSION_SECRET (dev only). Refused
#               at startup when NODE_ENV=production.
# 'aws-kms'   → AWS KMS via Vercel OIDC federation. K2 v1 prod target.
#               Requires AWS_REGION + AWS_ROLE_ARN + AWS_KMS_KEY_ID; the
#               OIDC token is auto-injected by Vercel into VERCEL_OIDC_TOKEN
#               at request scope (no static AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID /
#               AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY ever in env).
A2A_KMS_BACKEND=local-aes

# ─── Legacy session-table fallback (Sprint 1 W2.2 S1.6) ──────────────
# Controls whether `apps/a2a-agent/src/middleware/require-session.ts`
# falls back to the legacy a2a `sessions` table (Path B) after the
# SessionGrant lookup (Path A) returns no match.
#   - 'true'  → Path B is enabled. Demo-login and other
#               delegation-bootstrapped session-table rows are accepted.
#   - 'false' → Path B is rejected with 401; the middleware writes an
#               audit-deny row tagged 'legacy-session-fallback-disabled'.
# Default: true in dev / false in production. Explicit
# ALLOW_LEGACY_A2A_SESSIONS=true in production is honoured as an
# operator-controlled escape hatch for incident response / staged
# migration; the audit log captures every legacy reach either way.
# ALLOW_LEGACY_A2A_SESSIONS=true

# ─── AWS KMS (v1 prod KMS backend) ───────────────────────────────────
# Uncomment + populate when A2A_KMS_BACKEND=aws-kms. None of these are
# secrets — they are routing identifiers. The real security boundary is
# the IAM role trust policy (Vercel OIDC sub + aud conditions) and the
# CMK key policy. See KMS-IMPLEMENTATION-PLAN.md §8.1.
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
# AWS_ROLE_ARN=arn:aws:iam::111122223333:role/SmartAgentA2A
# AWS_KMS_KEY_ID=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/9a8b7c6d-1234-5678-90ab-cdef01234567
# K4 PR-2 — asymmetric ECC_SECG_P256K1 signing key. SEPARATE KMS key from
# AWS_KMS_KEY_ID. Different key spec (ECC_SECG_P256K1), different IAM
# permissions (kms:Sign, kms:GetPublicKey). The master-EOA private key
# never leaves AWS; the public key is fetched once at startup and the
# derived EOA address is cached for the process lifetime. Rotation is an
# on-chain operation (new CMK → new address → addOwner / removeOwner via
# the existing AgentAccount onlySelf path). See K4 PR-2 / §9 (rotation).
# AWS_KMS_SIGNER_KEY_ID=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/0123abcd-4567-89ef-0123-456789abcdef

# ─── MCP routing ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PERSON_MCP_URL=http://localhost:3200
ORG_MCP_URL=http://localhost:3400
PEOPLE_GROUP_MCP_URL=http://localhost:3300

# ─── Contract addresses (populated by scripts/deploy-local.sh) ───────
# ENTRYPOINT_ADDRESS=0x...
# AGENT_FACTORY_ADDRESS=0x...
# DELEGATION_MANAGER_ADDRESS=0x...
# ... see docs/architecture/02-onchain-architecture.md for the full set.

# ─── A2A master EOA (KMS migration K4 — env-resident dev fallback) ───
# In prod (K4 PR-2) the master EOA is an AWS KMS asymmetric
# ECC_SECG_P256K1 key — the env var is only the dev fallback consumed
# by `createLocalSecp256k1Signer`.
# A2A_MASTER_PRIVATE_KEY=0x...

# ─── Per-tool executor keys (KMS migration K5) ───────────────────────
# Each sensitive-tier tool family has its OWN signer identity — a
# compromised key for one family CANNOT sign for another. In dev each
# family reads a hex private key (`TOOL_EXECUTOR_<TOOL_ID>_PRIVATE_KEY`,
# anvil accounts #5-#8, populated by scripts/deploy-local.sh).
# In prod each family reads a SEPARATE AWS KMS asymmetric
# `ECC_SECG_P256K1` key id (`AWS_KMS_TOOL_EXECUTOR_<TOOL_ID>_KEY_ID`) —
# the IAM policy scopes `kms:Sign` to that single ARN per tool key,
# bounding the blast radius of a compromised agent process.
#
# Tool families (canonical list lives in
# `@smart-agent/sdk/key-custody` → TOOL_EXECUTOR_IDS):
#   round-awards    — round:close, round:cancel, round:set_awards_root
#   disbursement    — disbursement:claim
#   pool-lifecycle  — pool:close
#   grant-awards    — grant_proposal:award, grant_proposal:revoke_award
#   auth-bootstrap  — web bootstrap-auth handlers (siwe-verify,
#                     passkey-signup, google-callback). Consumed by the
#                     WEB tier (apps/web/.env), not the a2a-agent — but
#                     listed here for completeness of the canonical
#                     TOOL_EXECUTOR_IDS registry.
#
# Dev (local-aes) form — uncomment + populate when running outside the
# scripts/deploy-local.sh flow (the script seeds these automatically):
# TOOL_EXECUTOR_ROUND_AWARDS_PRIVATE_KEY=0x...
# TOOL_EXECUTOR_DISBURSEMENT_PRIVATE_KEY=0x...
# TOOL_EXECUTOR_POOL_LIFECYCLE_PRIVATE_KEY=0x...
# TOOL_EXECUTOR_GRANT_AWARDS_PRIVATE_KEY=0x...
# TOOL_EXECUTOR_AUTH_BOOTSTRAP_PRIVATE_KEY=0x...   # consumed by web tier
#
# Prod (aws-kms) form — every tool's KMS key id must be present when
# A2A_KMS_BACKEND=aws-kms; config.ts fails fast at boot if any is
# missing. Each key is a SEPARATE KMS CMK (do NOT reuse the master
# signer key or another tool's key — defense in depth requires
# per-family ARNs). See docs/operations/kms-signer-setup.md
# § "Tool-executor signer keys (K5)".
# AWS_KMS_TOOL_EXECUTOR_ROUND_AWARDS_KEY_ID=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/aaaa1111-...
# AWS_KMS_TOOL_EXECUTOR_DISBURSEMENT_KEY_ID=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/bbbb2222-...
# AWS_KMS_TOOL_EXECUTOR_POOL_LIFECYCLE_KEY_ID=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/cccc3333-...
# AWS_KMS_TOOL_EXECUTOR_GRANT_AWARDS_KEY_ID=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/dddd4444-...
# AWS_KMS_TOOL_EXECUTOR_AUTH_BOOTSTRAP_KEY_ID=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/eeee5555-...  # consumed by web tier

# ─── Inter-service HMAC keys ─────────────────────────────────────────
# Local-aes / dev: static hex secrets. Used by `createLocalHmacProvider`
# when A2A_KMS_BACKEND='local-aes'. Refused at startup in production
# (NODE_ENV=production) — same posture as the K2 envelope provider.
# WEB_TO_A2A_HMAC_KEY=0x...
# A2A_INTERSERVICE_HMAC_KEY_PERSON=0x...
# A2A_INTERSERVICE_HMAC_KEY_ORG=0x...
# A2A_INTERSERVICE_HMAC_KEY_FAMILY=0x...
# A2A_INTERSERVICE_HMAC_KEY_PEOPLE_GROUP=0x...
# A2A_INTERSERVICE_HMAC_KEY_VERIFIER=0x...
# A2A_INTERSERVICE_HMAC_KEY_SKILL=0x...
# A2A_INTERSERVICE_HMAC_KEY_GEO=0x...
#
# AWS KMS / prod (KMS migration K3-extension): each MAC key is a SEPARATE
# AWS KMS HMAC key (`KeySpec=HMAC_256`, `KeyUsage=GENERATE_VERIFY_MAC`,
# `MacAlgorithms=[HMAC_SHA_256]`). Per-key IAM scoping means a leaked
# role can call kms:GenerateMac/VerifyMac on ONLY the keys its identity
# policy allows. See `docs/operations/kms-signer-setup.md` § "Inter-
# service MAC keys" for the IAM templates. a2a-agent's role needs verify
# access to all eight; each MCP needs generate access to its OWN
# a2a-to-X key only; the web role needs generate access to web-to-a2a
# only. Validated fail-fast in `apps/a2a-agent/src/config.ts` when
# A2A_KMS_BACKEND='aws-kms'.
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_WEB_TO_A2A=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_A2A_TO_PERSON=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_A2A_TO_ORG=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_A2A_TO_FAMILY=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_A2A_TO_PEOPLE_GROUP=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_A2A_TO_VERIFIER=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_A2A_TO_SKILL=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...
# AWS_KMS_MAC_KEY_ID_A2A_TO_GEO=arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:111122223333:key/...

# ─── Rate-limit thresholds (per-IP sliding window) ───────────────────
# `apps/a2a-agent/src/middleware/rate-limit.ts` reads each call site's
# `RATE_LIMIT_<PREFIX>_MAX` and `RATE_LIMIT_<PREFIX>_WINDOW_MS`. Defaults
# below are shipping-tight for production; the dev default (used when
# `NODE_ENV != 'production'`) raises the ceiling ~5x so Playwright demo
# loops (tight Maria→David→Sarah→Maria sign-in + post-write
# `mcp/hub/sync:schedule` bursts) don't flap on 429. Setting any var
# explicitly overrides both prod and dev defaults for that call site.
# Non-numeric or <=0 values fail-fast at boot.
#
# Window is milliseconds; max is requests per IP per window.
# RATE_LIMIT_GENERAL_MAX=60               # dev default 300
# RATE_LIMIT_GENERAL_WINDOW_MS=60000
# RATE_LIMIT_SESSION_INIT_MAX=10          # dev default 60
# RATE_LIMIT_SESSION_INIT_WINDOW_MS=60000
# RATE_LIMIT_AUTH_MAX=10                  # dev default 60
# RATE_LIMIT_AUTH_WINDOW_MS=60000
# RATE_LIMIT_MCP_PROXY_MAX=60             # dev default 300
# RATE_LIMIT_MCP_PROXY_WINDOW_MS=60000
